{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489815"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:31:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"748"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/748"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.04,0.31,0.09,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114582"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/748"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96583"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"2075"},{"type":"tags","id":"2098"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36558"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42138"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45053"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114582"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E7\u003C/strong\u003E2-year-old woman is referred to a Breast and Endocrine clinic for management of a recently discovered 0.5 cm solid lesion in the right lower lobe of her thyroid. This was identified following a CT scan performed after a whiplash injury sustained in a motor vehicle crash. There were no other abnormalities and the lesion was confirmed by ultrasound scan. A fine needle biopsy of the lesion was organised due to patient concern and this showed psammoma bodies, consistent with papillary thyroid carcinoma. Her medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes, for which she take perindopril and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination of her neck is unremarkable and there are no abnormal physical findings on general examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active surveillance","Radioiodine scan","Right thyroid lobectomy","Total thyroidectomy","Total thyroidectomy and neck lymph node dissection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe main reason for the apparent increase in the incidence of thyroid cancer (in developed countries) has been the increased use of ultrasound and other imaging modalities and detection of asymptomatic solitary solid nodules in the thyroid. It has been estimated that 70 - 90% of the thyroid cancers found in the United States, Western Europe and Australia are incidental findings. Less than 4% of patients with these so-called papillary microcarcinomas (less that 1 cm) showed clinical progression of their disease over a 75-month period. This patient could be offered a number of treatment options, which include active surveillance, thyroid lobectomy and total thyroidectomy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis older patient does have some health issues and a conservative approach would be most appropriate. \u003Cstrong\u003EActive surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E involves regular ultrasound examination every 6 - 12 months with the frequency spacing out to 12 - 24 months if there is no tumour growth or disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EActive surveillance is quite an appropriate alternative to surgery for patients with such lesions - and it does give the patient time to reflect over the risks and benefits of resection. This approach is especially true in a young, asymptomatic patient with an incidentally discovered small papillary thyroid cancer and no concerning features on biopsy. Active surveillance avoids potential surgical complications, life-long thyroxine replacement and allows for monitoring of the lesion over time to determine if it is progressing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe does not need a \u003Cstrong\u003Eradioiodine scan\u003C/strong\u003E as she does not have any symptoms of an overactive thyroid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor other types of small, differentiated thyroid cancers, surgery \u003Cstrong\u003E(e.g. thyroid lobectomy, thyroidectomy +/- lymph node dissection)\u003C/strong\u003E may be a better option than ongoing surveillance. However, for this specific patient with a small papillary microcarcinoma, active surveillance is a reasonable initial approach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small papillary thyroid cancers can be treated by active surveillance."],"references":["Ospina NS, Iniguez-Ariza NM, Castro MR. Thyroid nodules: diagnostic evaluation based on thyroid cancer risk assessment. BMJ 2020; 368:l6670. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31911452/","Sakai T, Sugitani I, Ebina A, Fukuoka O, Toda K, Mitani H, et al. Active Surveillance for T1bN0M0 Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma. Thyroid. 2019;29(1):59-63. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30560718/","Tuttle RM, Fagin JA, Minkowitz G, Wong RJ, Roman B, Patel S, et al. Natural History and Tumor Volume Kinetics of Papillary Thyroid Cancers During Active Surveillance. JAMA Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2017;143(10):1015-1020. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28859191/","Baidoun F, Abdel-Rahman O. The role of surgery in small differentiated thyroid cancer. Endocrine. 2022;77(3):469-479. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35657579/","Fields TD, Underwood HJ, Pitt SC. Management of Small Papillary Thyroid Cancers. Surg Clin N Am 104; 2024:725\u201340 https://doi.org/10.1016/j.suc.2024.02.003"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96583"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"748"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96583"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T20:05:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T20:05:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"748"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114582"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","